Norwich; with a rude head upon the obverſe, and an ill formed horſe on the reverſe, with Inſcriptions Ic. Duro. T. whether implying Iceni, Durotriges, Taſcia, or Trinobantes, we leave to higher conjecture. Vulgar Chronology will have Norwich Caſtle as old as Julius Caeſar;
but his diſtance from theſe parts, and its Gothick form of ſtructure, abridgeth ſuch Antiquity. The Britiſh Coyns afford conjecture of early habitation in theſe parts, though the City of Norwich aroſe from the ruines of Venta, and though perhaps not without ſome habitation before, was enlarged, builded, and nominated by the Saxons. In what bulk or populoſity it ſtood in the old Eaſt-angle Monarchy, tradition and hiſtory are ſilent. Conſiderable it was in the Daniſh Eruptions, when Sueno burnt Thetford and Norwich Brampron Abbas Journallenſis,, and Ʋlfketel the Governour thereof, was able to make ſome reſiſtance, and after endeavoured to burn the Daniſh Navy.
